04433nam a22005775i 9780231539548DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014043407  a(OCoLC)984681998  a97802315395487 a10.1515/97802315395482doi  a(DE-B1597)460994  a(OCoLC)947837293  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPK1701b.K38 2015 4aPK1701b.K38 2015eb 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a891.4/4092231 aKaviraj, Sudipta, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Invention of Private Life :bLiterature and Ideas /cSudipta Kaviraj.  aPilot project. eBook available to selected US libraries only 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (376 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Literature as the Mirror of Modernity -- t1. On the Advantages of Being a Barbarian -- t2. Literature and the Moral Imaginations of Modernity -- t3. The Two Histories of Literary Culture in Bengal -- t4. A Strange Love of Abstractions -- t5. Tagore and Transformations in the Ideals of Love -- t6. The Poetry of Interiority The Creation of a Language of Modern Subjectivity in Tagore’s Poetry -- t7. Laughter and Subjectivity -- t8. Reading a Song of the City -- t9. The Art of Despair -- t10. The Invention of Private Life -- t11. The Second Mahabharata -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe essays in this volume, which lie at the intersection of the study of literature, social theory, and intellectual history, locate serious reflections on modernity's complexities in the vibrant currents of modern Indian literature, particularly in the realms of fiction, poetry, and autobiography. Sudipta Kaviraj shows that Indian writers did more than adopt new literary trends in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries. They deployed these innovations to interrogate fundamental philosophical questions of modernity. Issues central to modern European social theory grew into significant themes within Indian literary reflection, such as the influence of modernity on the nature of the self, the nature of historicity, the problem of evil, the character of power under the conditions of modern history, and the experience of power as felt by an individual subject of the modern state. How does modern politics affect the personality of a sensitive individual? Is love possible between intensely self-conscious people, and how do individuals cope with the transience of affections or the fragility of social ties? Kaviraj argues that these inquiries inform the heart of modern Indian literary tradition and that writers, such as Bankimchandra Chattopadhyay, Rabindranath Tagore, and Sibnath Sastri, performed immeasurably important work helping readers to think through the predicament of modern times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBengali literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and society. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP Single-User eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070982708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978023153954840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231539548423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231539548/original  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-070982-7  CUP Single-User eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles